d. Landry focuses not only on the social and political significance of the theatre of anger and the ways in which it rages against racism, antisemitism, Islamophobia, sexism, and homophobia, but also on its aesthetic and theoretical innovation. Through readings of key works, Theatre of Anger asks what it means in our present world to construct political theatre.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aAnger in literature. 0aAngerxSocial aspects. 0aGerman dramay21st centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aPolitical plays, GermanxHistory and criticism. 0aSocial justice in literature. 7aDRAMA / European / German.2bisacsh  aBrecht.  aGerman theatre.  aJewish German.  aSasha Marianna Salzmann.  aTurkish German.  aanger.  aart and resistance.  apolitical performance.  apostmigrant theatre.  asocial justice.  atheatre.  atransnational theater.40uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148753675640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487536756423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781487536756.jpg  aGBV-deGruyter-alles